# Cut Theory Implementation

This repository contains the Python code for Cut Theory, as described in my arXiv paper.
Original author: William M. Bartholomew Jr.
First formulated in 2015; independent development 2015–2025.
Commit history preserved forever.

See cut_theory.py for the main implementation.

Cut Theory is a conceptual framework for understanding division as a process of structured partitioning.
Rather than focusing only on numerical results, it models division as a “cut” that produces both the size 
and structure of pieces, offering a clearer and more intuitive way to reason about fractions and division.

1 thing cut 1 time gives you 2 things at 1/2 of their original size: 1 cut 1 = (2, 1/2)
